%HRTitleEvent Holdup
%bridge-classroom-stable: true
{South is to play 3NT. West leads the \S3. East wins the first trick with the \SA and returns the \S8.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 7

You can win 3 more \D tricks if the finesse works, but even if it doesn't work you can still get the 2 that you need. Of course if East does win the \DK it would sure be great if he had no \S to lead. So you duck the second \S and take your \SK when they play a third round.

After winning the \SK you are conveniently in your hand, so you play the \DQ and let it ride when West plays a low card. Alas, East takes the trick with his \DK.

It's too bad the finesse didn't work, but it's not too too bad! Because East is out of \Ss and must lead one of the other suits. You don't care which he leads because you can now win 8 more tricks and make your contract.

As long as you were going to finesse into East you could establish the \Ds without allowing West to gain the lead.

And as long as you had held up on the \SK until the third round you could ensure that East was out of \Ss if he had started with only 3.}
[Play "W"]S3

