{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \DK.

Winners:   \S=3  \H=2  \D=1  \C=0  Total = 6

You will need some \C tricks to make the contract. If East has 5 \Ds and also the \CA then you will go down. It doesn't matter if he has the \CQ because you can finesse him out of that.

But in the case where West has both the \C A Q you need to make sure he has no \D when he takes his first trick. So hold up the \DA until the third round, everybody following.

Now start on the \Cs. Play your \C9 and let it ride. West wins the \CQ and returns a \S. Good, he didn't have the fourth \D.

Win with dummy's \SQ and force out the \CA.

The rest of the tricks are yours, nine in all.

If West had only held 2 \Ds it would have been OK to hold up your \DA just once.

But with this layout you needed to hold up twice.}
[Play "W"]DK

